Description:
Defending champion Carlos Alcaraz has won the third set in the Roland Garros final to gain a foothold against rival Jannik Sinner. The Italian leads the Spaniard 6-4, 7-6(4), 4-6 after three hours and five minutes of high-octane action on Court Philippe-Chatrier.

Alcaraz and Sinner have enjoyed a riveting rivalry since their maiden meeting at the ATP Masters 1000 in Paris in 2021, with the Spaniard leading the Italian 7-4 in the pair's Lexus ATP Head2Head series. However, this is their first clash in a major final and it has lived up to the hype so far.

After Sinner won the opening set, he remained composed in the second set, recovering from squandering a 5-2 lead to prevail in the tie-break and double his advantage. However, Alcaraz has refused to go away, showing the champion's spirit that has helped him to four major titles in the early years of his career.

The Spaniard struck his groundstrokes with more aggression and penetration to frequently force Sinner out of position and off balance, clinching the third set after initially failing to serve out at 5-3.



Alcaraz is bidding to become the eighth man in the Open Era (since 1968) and just the third this century to successfully defend his Roland Garros crown. If the 22-year-old can turn the tables and clinch his fifth major, he will maintain his flawless record in Slam finals. He has never won a match at a major after losing the first two sets but holds a 12-1 record in fifth sets, while Sinner is 6-9 at the same stage.

Three-time Slam champion Sinner is also unbeaten in major finals and is on a 20-match winning streak at this level, having won the US Open in September and the Australian Open in January. The No. 1 in the PIF ATP Rankings is looking to become just the fifth man in the Open Era to clinch three consecutive major titles and the second Italian man in the Open Era to lift the Coupe des Mousquetaires trophy after Adriano Panatta in 1976.



















































































